{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Publish governance: GOVERNANCE.md, MAINTAINERS.md, CoC contact fix (CODEOWNERS explicitly skipped)\n\n## Why\n\nGovernance is implicit today; an outsider cannot see who decides, how maintainers are added, or where a Code of Conduct report goes if it concerns the maintainer himself. Peer convergence (curl's GOVERNANCE.md https://github.com/curl/curl/blob/master/docs/GOVERNANCE.md; the CNCF small-project template https://github.com/cncf/project-template/blob/main/GOVERNANCE.md; opensource.guide) gives a one-page recipe. The one thing no template covers — and the thing readers of an org-backed solo project probe — is the Nava-PBC-backed-but-individual-led ambiguity, so it gets its own section.\n\n## What\n\n- `GOVERNANCE.md` (~1 page) with the seven convergent sections:\n  1. Overview — maintainer-led, created and stewarded at Nava PBC; names the current lead maintainer; one-line reorientation: review happens on Gerrit, GitHub is a read-only mirror.\n  2. Roles — contributor / maintainer / lead maintainer, with rebar-specific powers: Gerrit submit rights (Contributors group), ticket-store write access, release authority.\n  3. Decision-making — consensus among maintainers; lead maintainer has final say (curl's model in role language); routine decisions happen in Gerrit review and rebar tickets; ADRs under `docs/adr/` record architectural choices.\n  4. Becoming a maintainer — sustained quality contributions through Gerrit review (\"a few quality changes merged as proof\" — curl's bar), invited by the lead maintainer.\n  5. Stepping down / emeritus — inactivity → access removed for security reasons, non-punitive, listed as emeritus.\n  6. Nava PBC's role — what the org provides (Gerrit host, maintainer employment) and does not control (contributors participate as individuals — CNCF framing). Includes the succession decision (see open decisions).\n  7. Changing this document — via a Gerrit change, lead maintainer approves.\n- `MAINTAINERS.md`: table (name, GitHub handle, Gerrit username, scope, affiliation), one row today; \"Emeritus maintainers\" placeholder section; \"changes are proposed as a Gerrit change against this file — see GOVERNANCE.md\". Separate file despite one row (health-file scanners look for it by name).\n- `CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md`: keep the Contributor Covenant; change the enforcement contact to role-based with a Nava backstop and add: \"if a report concerns the lead maintainer, contact <Nava backstop> instead.\" **Also update the matching contact line in `SUPPORT.md` (~line 31 hard-codes hello@navapbc.com as the CoC contact)** so the two files never disagree.\n- Assess CC 2.1 → 3.0 (3.0 is the 2026 default — Django/Mastodon/Hanami adopted; https://www.contributor-covenant.org/version/3/0/code_of_conduct/); record the upgrade decision.\n- Decision persistence (in-repo, not ticket-only): record the three design decisions — lead-maintainer-vs-BDFL language; CC version; CODEOWNERS non-goal — in ADR `docs/adr/0038-governance-artifacts.md` (one ADR, three short sections), with a ticket comment pointing at it.\n- CODEOWNERS non-goal rationale (corrected mechanism): GitHub PRs cannot merge here (a repository ruleset rejects PR merges today, and the PR-posture story adds a bot that auto-closes new PRs) — CODEOWNERS only auto-requests reviewers and gates merges on PRs, so it would be dead config falsely implying PR review. Gerrit's code-owners plugin likewise skipped (one human owns everything).\n- Open org decisions to resolve with Nava before close (record answers in GOVERNANCE.md §6 + the ADR): (a) succession — whether project authority (PyPI name `nava-rebar`, the Gerrit host, the GitHub org repo) rests with the person or with Nava PBC; (b) the named Nava CoC backstop contact.\n\n## Scope\n\nIN: GOVERNANCE.md, MAINTAINERS.md, CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md contact + version assessment, SUPPORT.md contact-line sync, ADR 0038.\nOUT: CODEOWNERS (either flavor); formal voting machinery; a foundation-style CoC committee; the rest of SUPPORT.md (owned by the intake story).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] GOVERNANCE.md present with all seven sections — prove: grep for section headings incl. \"Nava\" and \"emeritus\"; Gerrit-mirror reorientation in the first ~10 lines.\n- [ ] MAINTAINERS.md present — prove: `grep -qi \"emeritus\" MAINTAINERS.md` and the table has ≥1 row + change-process pointer.\n- [ ] CoC enforcement contact is role-based with a named Nava backstop and the maintainer-concerning-report escape — prove: `grep -q \"lead maintainer\" CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md`; SUPPORT.md's CoC contact line matches CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md exactly (same address string in both files).\n- [ ] ADR 0038 committed with the three decisions + rationale — prove: `test -f docs/adr/0038-governance-artifacts.md`.\n- [ ] Succession + backstop answers from Nava recorded in GOVERNANCE.md §6 (or the ticket documents who was asked and the interim wording used, if the org answer is pending — the doc must not silently omit the section)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783631028607727001,"uuid":"9f89f3ff-7b77-4d44-bfa6-feff05554efb"}